# Research & Reflection Journal

## Activity 1: Research on Design Patterns

### Design Pattern 1: Singleton Pattern

**Purpose:**
The Singleton pattern makes sure that only one instance of a class exists while allowing the rest of the program to access it. This is useful when you only need one shared object.

**Real-World Application:**
A good example is a database connection manager. Instead of creating multiple connections, the application uses one shared manager to handle all database requests.

**Example:**
A logging service can use the Singleton pattern so that every part of the program writes to the same log file instead of creating multiple loggers.

**Summary:**
I learned that the Singleton pattern helps save resources and keeps everything consistent by making sure there is only one instance of an important object.

---

### Design Pattern 2: Factory Method Pattern

**Purpose:**
The Factory Method pattern creates objects without the rest of the program needing to know exactly how they are created. A factory handles the object creation behind the scenes.

**Real-World Application:**
An online store could use this pattern to create different payment options like Credit Card, PayPal, or Apple Pay depending on what the customer chooses.

**Example:**
A notification system could create an Email, SMS, or Push Notification object based on the user's preferred notification method.

**Summary:**
This pattern makes programs easier to expand because new object types can be added without changing a lot of existing code.

---

### Design Pattern 3: Observer Pattern

**Purpose:**
The Observer pattern lets multiple objects automatically receive updates whenever something changes.

**Real-World Application:**
Weather apps are a great example because users receive updated forecasts whenever new weather information becomes available.

**Example:**
When a YouTube creator uploads a new video, subscribers are automatically notified.

**Summary:**
The Observer pattern is useful whenever information needs to be shared with many users or parts of a program at the same time.

---

### Design Pattern 4: Strategy Pattern

**Purpose:**
The Strategy pattern allows a program to choose between different ways of completing the same task without changing the rest of the code.

**Real-World Application:**
GPS apps use different routing options, such as the fastest route, the shortest route, or avoiding toll roads.

**Example:**
An online shopping site lets customers pay using different methods like Credit Card, PayPal, or Apple Pay, with each option following its own strategy.

**Summary:**
I like this pattern because it makes programs more flexible and easier to update when new options need to be added.

### Reflection

Learning about these design patterns helped me understand why experienced developers don't solve every problem from scratch. Instead, they use proven solutions that make their code cleaner, easier to maintain, and easier to build on later. I found the Factory Method and Strategy patterns the most interesting because I can see myself using them in future JavaScript projects.

