# Activity 4: How to Contribute to Open Source

### Summary

The GitHub Open Source Guide showed me that contributing to open source involves much more than writing code. People can help by improving documentation, reporting bugs, testing software, writing tutorials, answering questions, reviewing pull requests, and even translating content.

The guide also explained how to tell whether a project is beginner-friendly by checking things like recent activity, contribution guidelines, active maintainers, and community involvement. It also introduced websites like Good First Issue, Up For Grabs, and CodeTriage that help beginners find projects looking for contributors.

### Reflection

Before reading this guide, I thought open source was mainly for experienced programmers. I was surprised to learn there are many ways beginners can contribute without writing complicated code. I think starting with documentation or beginner-friendly issues would be a good way to gain experience and become more confident.

